  "text": "## Controller Registration with Controller-Runtime Manager in Kubernetes\n\nThis tracing documents how controllers register with the controller manager in Kubernetes, following the patterns used by k8s.io/controller-manager (note: this is distinct from sigs.k8s.io/controller-runtime, though follows similar principles).\n\n### Key Components\n\n**1. Controller Interface (staging/src/k8s.io/controller-manager/controller/interfaces.go)**\nControllers must implement the base `Interface` interface which requires a `Name()` method. Controllers may optionally implement `Debuggable` interface (for debugging handlers) and `HealthCheckable` interface (for health checks).\n\n**2. Controller Descriptor Pattern (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go:421-429)**\nUnlike SetupWithManager in controller-runtime, Kubernetes uses a `ControllerDescriptor` struct to register controllers. Each descriptor contains:\n- Controller name and aliases\n- InitFunc: a function that creates and initializes the controller\n- Feature gate requirements\n- Disabled-by-default flags\n\nThis is defined as:\n```go\ntype ControllerDescriptor struct {\n    name                      string\n    initFunc                  InitFunc\n    requiredFeatureGates      []featuregate.Feature\n    aliases                   []string\n    isDisabledByDefault       bool\n    isCloudProviderController bool\n    requiresSpecialHandling   bool\n}\n```\n\n**3. InitFunc (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go:419)**\nThe InitFunc is the equivalent of SetupWithManager in controller-runtime. It has the signature:\n```go\ntype InitFunc func(ctx context.Context, controllerContext ControllerContext, controllerName string) (controller controller.Interface, enabled bool, err error)\n```\nThis function is responsible for:\n- Creating the controller instance\n- Registering event handlers via informers\n- Starting the controller's workers\n- Returning the controller.Interface\n\n**4. ControllerContext (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go:366-401)**\nThe ControllerContext is the dependency injection container passed to InitFunc. It provides:\n- ClientBuilder: for creating Kubernetes API clients\n- InformerFactory: SharedInformerFactory for accessing informers\n- ObjectOrMetadataInformerFactory: for accessing metadata informers\n- ComponentConfig: configuration for the controller\n- RESTMapper: for mapping resources to REST endpoints\n\n**5. Reconciliation Pattern (staging/src/k8s.io/endpointslice/reconciler.go)**\nWhile not using the controller-runtime library, Kubernetes implementations follow a reconciliation pattern. The EndpointSlice reconciler demonstrates this:\n- A Reconciler struct holds dependencies (clients, listers, etc.)\n- A Reconcile method transforms current state to desired state\n- Informer event handlers enqueue items for processing\n\n**6. Sample Controller Implementation (staging/src/k8s.io/sample-controller/controller.go)**\nThe sample controller demonstrates the complete pattern:\n- NewController() creates the controller, sets up informer event handlers, creates workqueues\n- Run() starts worker goroutines that process work items\n- syncHandler performs the actual reconciliation logic\n- Event handlers call enqueueFoo() to add items to the workqueue\n\n### Registration Flow\n\n1. **Startup**: kube-controller-manager calls Run() in controllermanager.go:180\n2. **Descriptor Discovery**: NewControllerDescriptors() returns a map of all available controllers (controllermanager.go:495)\n3. **Context Creation**: CreateControllerContext() builds the ControllerContext with shared resources (controllermanager.go:228)\n4. **Controller Initialization**: StartControllers() iterates through descriptors and calls each InitFunc (controllermanager.go:234)\n5. **Event Handling**: Each controller's InitFunc registers event handlers on informers\n6. **Worker Loop**: Each controller runs worker goroutines that pull from workqueues\n7. **Reconciliation**: Workers call syncHandler to bring current state to desired state\n\n### Key Differences from sigs.k8s.io/controller-runtime\n\n- **Registration**: ControllerDescriptor + InitFunc vs. SetupWithManager()\n- **Dependency Injection**: ControllerContext passed explicitly vs. Manager holds references\n- **Workqueue**: Manually created and managed vs. auto-managed by reconciliation loop\n- **Event Handler Setup**: Done in InitFunc/NewController vs. done in SetupWithManager\n- **Reconcile Signature**: Custom per controller vs. standardized Reconcile(ctx, req) -> (Result, error)\n\n### Files in the Chain\n\nThe registration chain flows through:\n1. **controllermanager.go:Run()** - Main entry point for the manager\n2. **controllermanager.go:NewControllerDescriptors()** - Discovers all available controllers\n3. **controllermanager.go:CreateControllerContext()** - Creates shared dependency container\n4. **controllermanager.go:StartControllers()** - Initializes all enabled controllers\n5. **app/core.go, apps.go, batch.go, etc.** - Individual controller InitFunc implementations that call startXxxController()\n6. **sample-controller/controller.go** - Example of a complete controller implementation\n\nThis architecture enables pluggable, independently managed controllers that share common infrastructure like informers, clients, and workqueues."
}

